    {
      "question": "If the HCF of two numbers $a = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^x$ and $b = 2^2 \times 3^y \times 5^2$ is $2^2 \times 3^2 \times 5^2$, and their LCM is $2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^3$, then the value of $x + y$ is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "The HCF of two numbers is the product of the smallest power of each common prime factor.",
          "Given $HCF = 2^2 \times 3^2 \times 5^2$, compare with $a = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^x$ and $b = 2^2 \times 3^y \times 5^2$.",
          "For $HCF = 5^2$, the smallest power of 5 is $\\min(x, 2) = 2$, so $x \\geq 2$.",
          "For $HCF = 3^2$, the smallest power of 3 is $\\min(2, y) = 2$, so $y \\geq 2$.",
          "The LCM is the product of the greatest power of each prime factor involved.",
          "Given $LCM = 2^3 \times 3^2 \times 5^3$, compare with $a$ and $b$.",
          "For $LCM = 5^3$, the greatest power of 5 is $\\max(x, 2) = 3$, so $x = 3$.",
          "For $LCM = 3^2$, the greatest power of 3 is $\\max(2, y) = 2$, so $y \\leq 2$. Since $y \\geq 2$ from HCF, $y = 2$.",
          "Find $x + y = 3 + 2 = 5$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$HCF(a, b) = 2^{\\min(3,2)} \\times 3^{\\min(2,y)} \\times 5^{\\min(x,2)} = 2^2 \\times 3^2 \\times 5^2 \\Rightarrow \\min(2,y)=2, \\min(x,2)=2 \\\\ LCM(a, b) = 2^{\\max(3,2)} \\times 3^{\\max(2,y)} \\times 5^{\\max(x,2)} = 2^3 \\times 3^2 \\times 5^3 \\Rightarrow \\max(2,y)=2, \\max(x,2)=3 \\\\ x=3, y=2 \\\\ x+y = 3+2 = 5$"
      },
